solutionCode.javascript:
    ```javascript
function num_zeros(k) {
    let x = 0;
    for (let i = 5; Math.floor(k / i) >= 1; i *= 5) {
        x += Math.floor(k / i);
    }
    return x;
}
```

    The algorithm, to find the number of non-negative integers x that have the property f(x) = k, takes advantage of the fact that trailing zeros in a factorial can be determined by counting the factors of 5 (since there will always be enough factors of 2 to pair with factors of 5 in the factorial).

1. Initialize the count of non-negative integers x with the value 0.
2. Loop through the integer multiples of 5 (i = 5, 25, 125, ...) until k / i >= 1.
3. Inside the loop, add k // i (or k / i, floor-divided) to the count of x. This is the number of factors of 5 that create trailing zeros.
4. Return the count of x after the loop.

This algorithm should work identically for all of the given languages: C++, Java, Python, and JavaScript.

